<br>
I will tell you what it s going to be, A huge SLOW! $$$$EXPENSIVE$$$$$$ tin balloon filled with liquid hydrogen powered by a pair of little solid core reactors open at one end. Because of its asthmatic drive system the beast will be using a low energy transfer orbit for its Mars mission and the return payload will be so small that it will be almost negligible. Seriously now a little box of mars rocks would be nice but is it worth it?  <br>
<br>
The ship in fact will be just about 3/5ths the size of a ship that uses liquid hydrogen and oxygen as its fuel but it will be MUCH more expensive when all the systems development costs are factored in. Of course since the power plant is so weak the NASA folks will have to apply ‘minimum weight criterion ‘ to everything on board that ship and that will cause the cost to skyrocket. Another  thing to think about  is the condition of the astronauts after they have spent 2 or more years in zero gee! Their bones and cardiovascular systems would be so degenerated that they might never recover from it. <br>
<br>
A single Mars mission the NASA way is going to cost upwards of  $100,000,000,000 (that’s conservative). And this mission will put us no closer to developing an interplanetary economy than we are right now, in fact it will have no more real impact on the world condition than another trip over Niagara falls in a barrel.  If on the other hand  NASA were to invest in ‘ORION’ type ships that $100,000,000,000 would translate into a small fleet of multi use ships that could make the run to and from Mars or the asteroid belt in a matter of a few months not years and return with big robust payloads. <br>
<br>
I do see the NASA proposal as a step in the right direction because it might condition the public in a positive way and remove ‘Nuclear Power” from the restricted word list. <br>
<br>
NukePulse AKA  Steve<br>
